ents? Upon what bases and according to which texts do modern scholars determine when a personality or object is a god in an ancient culture? In what ways are deities with both first and last names treated the same and differently from deities with only first names? Under what circumstances are deities with common first names and different last names recognizable as distinct independent deities, and under what circumstances are they merely local manifestations of an overarching deity? The conclusions drawn about the singularity of local manifestations versus the multiplicity of independent deities are specific to each individual first name examined in accordance with the data and texts available for each divine first name.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 0aGod (Judaism)xName. 0aGodxNamevComparative studies. 4aAltorientalistik. 4aAncient Near Eastern deities. 4aDivine epithets. 4aGeschichte. 4aTheologie. 70(DE-601)3261000080(DE-588)4596724-6aGöttlichkeit2gnd 7aHISTORY / Civilization.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2015z9783110438604oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97815015002200 cprintz978161451293640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781614512363423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781614512363.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DGDb2015  aZDB-23-DGGb2015